## Class Name Utility (`cn`)

This utility function (`cn`) is designed to simplify the process of conditionally joining Tailwind CSS class names.

### Purpose

The primary purpose of this function is to provide a convenient way to combine multiple class names, allowing for conditional inclusion and automatically merging overlapping class names using `clsx` and `tailwind-merge`. This is particularly useful in UI development where class names often depend on component props or application state.

### Key Exports

*   **`cn(...inputs: ClassValue[])`**: This is the main export. It takes a variable number of arguments of type `ClassValue` (which can be strings, objects, arrays, booleans, null, or undefined) and returns a single, merged string of class names.

### Usage Example

```typescript
import { cn } from './utils'; // Assuming utils.ts is in the same directory

const isActive = true;
const isDisabled = false;

const buttonClasses = cn(
  'py-2 px-4 rounded-md',
  isActive && 'bg-blue-500 text-white',
  isDisabled && 'opacity-50 cursor-not-allowed',
  'hover:bg-blue-600'
);

// buttonClasses will evaluate to: 'py-2 px-4 rounded-md hover:bg-blue-600'
// If isActive were true, it would include 'bg-blue-500 text-white'.
// If isDisabled were true, it would include 'opacity-50 cursor-not-allowed'.

console.log(buttonClasses);
```

This function leverages `clsx` for intelligent class name concatenation and `tailwind-merge` to handle conflicts and ensure that the most appropriate Tailwind CSS classes are applied.
